<li id="cite_note-53"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-53">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">Taylor (2003), p. 62.</span></li>
<li id="cite_note-Salt1-54"><span class="mw-cite-backlink">^ <a href="#cite_ref-Salt1_54-0"><sup><i><b>a</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-Salt1_54-1"><sup><i><b>b</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-Salt1_54-2"><sup><i><b>c</b></i></sup></a></span> <span class="reference-text"><a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://www.animal-rights-library.com/texts-c/salt01.htm">Salt 1894, chapter 1</a>. Salt cited Spencer's definition of rights: "Every man is free to do that which he wills, provided he infringes not the equal liberty of any other man&#160;... Whoever admits that each man must have a certain restricted freedom, asserts that it is right he should have this restricted freedom&#160;... And hence the several particular freedoms deducible may fitly be called, as they commonly are called, his rights."</span></li>
